{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94bdc47a-fa29-491b-ad51-af0f921f7927","content":"The issue is the **F# file compilation order** in the `.fsproj`. In F#, files can only reference types/modules from files listed **above** them. Currently `Services.fs` is listed before `Domain.fs`, but `Services.fs` depends on `Domain.fs`.\n\nFixing the order:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_vYmvMWZDnIAu1gNKzfezfu","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-ae03d95a6fff4cb897283a752877f51a/fsharp/BrokenOrder/BrokenOrder.fsproj","old_str":"    <Compile Include=\"Services.fs\" />\n    <Compile Include=\"Domain.fs\" />","new_str":"    <Compile Include=\"Domain.fs\" />\n    <Compile Include=\"Services.fs\" />"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-ae03d95a6fff4cb897283a752877f51a/fsharp/BrokenOrder/BrokenOrder.fsproj."}],"interactionId":"267f0d82-1fca-4511-97cd-606700651dd5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The issue is clear. In F#, file compilation order matters. Files can only reference modules/types defined in files that appear *before* them in the compilation order.\n\nThe `.fsproj` file lists:\n1. `Services.fs` — references `BrokenOrder.Domain` (from `Domain.fs`)\n2. `Domain.fs` — defines `BrokenOrder.Domain`\n3. `Program.fs` — references both `Domain` and `Services`\n\n`Services.fs` is listed before `Domain.fs`, but `Services.fs` depends on types from `Domain.fs`. This will fail because `Domain.fs` hasn't been compiled yet when `Services.fs` is processed.\n\n\nThe fix is straightforward: I need to reorder the files so `Domain.fs` compiles first, then `Services.fs` can reference it, and finally `Program.fs` can use both.","outputTokens":459,"requestId":"7405:17DD88:16252D8:18B11BA:6A051E2F"},"id":"347f0cd6-187a-487a-9ae8-740130851b46","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:58:32.526Z","parentId":"bea3bda6-59ac-4406-b575-7ea5e8231c9a"}
